ושת נחלת אבות -- tכוהנים וסדרי מקדש בספר מלאכי לפי מקורות נאו־בבליים -- tחשיבותם המשפטית של המילים "וְהֻגַּד לְךָ": קריאה חדשה בדב' יז, 7 -- tמשחקי מילים במראות עמוס -- tפרשיות חוזרות ומשמעותן לחיבור ההיסטוריוגרפיה הדויטרונומיסטית והכרוניסטית -- tעל הזיקה שבין עלילת אקהת ובין סיפורי אברהם -- tבין אלוהים לאדם: על הפערים שבראייה, בריסון עצמי ובנאמנות -- t10 עריכה וחיבור במשלי כב - כג -- tהגהות רש"י לפירושו על ספר הושע -- tנפילת שומרון: בין היסטוריה להיסטוריוגרפיה -- tלרגע הופיעה ונעלמה - סיפורה של מרב בת שאול* -- tצידוק הדין - פעולות עיבוד בספרי שמואל ומלכים -- t"תועבת מצרים": אור חדש על בעיה ישנה -- tמפתח מחברים0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe title, Marbeh M16;okmah, meaning "increases wisdom," reflects the fact that Victor Avigdor Hurowitz was a scholar who increased wisdom and who continues to increase the wisdom of scholars throughout the world even after his untimely death at the age of 64. The book was edited by five of Professor Hurowitz's colleagues: Profs. Shamir Yona and Mayer I. Gruber of Ben-Gurion University of the Negev, Edward L. Greenstein of Bar-Ilan University, Peter Machinist of Harvard University, and Shalom M. Paul of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem. The two-volume collection contains 49 groundbreaking essays written by 53 distinguished authors from various institutions of higher learning in Israel and around the world. The authors include Victor's teachers, colleagues, and students, and the essays deal with a great variety of subjects. The breadth of subject matter featured in Marbeh M16;okmah is a most appropriate tribute to Victor Avigdor Hurowitz, whose published scholarship encompassed a wide variety of fields of interest pertaining to the study of the Hebrew Bible and the ancient Near East: Wisdom Literature, Psalmody, prophecy and prophets, the priesthood, eschatology, historiography, ancient inscriptions, medieval Hebrew biblical exegesis, religious rites, building and architecture, temples, the art of warfare, Semitic philology, Sumerian proverbs, epigraphy, rhetoric and stylistics, poetry, lamentations, the interconnections between Hebrew Scripture and the ancient Near East, the cultures of ancient Egypt and ancient Mesopotamia, innerbiblical parallels, and many other subjects.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAssyro-Babylonian literaturexHistory and criticism. 0aSemitic philology. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh1 aAbusch, Tzvi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAster, Shawn Zelig, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAḥituv, Shmuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeckman, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerlin, Adele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCogan, Mordechai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Chaim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCohen, Sol, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDay, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForti, Tova, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFried, Lisbeth S, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGabbay, Uri, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGitin, Seymour, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlatt-Gilad, David A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodnick Westenholz, Joan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraetz, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGree